## CORE DESIGN PRINCIPLE (READ THIS FIRST)

The hierarchy is a free-form navigation tree. There are no fixed levels.

Do NOT design for:
  Area → Machine → Component → Sub-Component

DO design for:
  Any node can have any number of child nodes.
  Any node can be the parent or the leaf.
  The tree shape is defined by the administrator, not by the software.

Real-world examples that must be supported without any schema changes:

  Wetmill → Romeo → Saw Heads → Head 1 → Motor → Drive End Bearing
  Wetmill → Romeo → Infeed → Conveyor → Gearbox → Output Shaft
  Kilns → Kiln 3 → Fan → Motor → Cooling Fan
  Wetmill → Romeo → Saw Heads → Head 2 → Motor → Drive End Bearing → Bearing Housing → Seal → Grease Nipple

---

## CRITICAL: HOW EQUIPMENT NUMBERS ANCHOR THE HIERARCHY

The existing equipment register is the single source of truth. Equipment numbers
(compound IDs like WM-ROM-001) do NOT change. They are the anchor for all
breakdowns, PM tasks, and reports — now and in the future.

The hierarchy wraps AROUND the equipment register. It is a navigation layer only.

The relationship works like this:

  NAVIGATION TREE          ANCHOR
  ────────────────         ──────────────────────────
  Wetmill                  (navigation only, no equipment number)
    → Romeo                (navigation only, no equipment number)
      → Saw Heads          (navigation only, no equipment number)
        → Head 1           (navigation only, no equipment number)
          → Motor    ────► WM-ROM-SH1-MOT-001  ← equipment record
                           (this is where breakdowns and PMs attach)

Rules:
- Only LEAF nodes that represent a trackable, maintainable asset get an equipment_id
- Mid-level nodes are navigation structure only — no equipment number
- One equipment_id maps to exactly one leaf node (one-to-one)
- The equipment_id never changes — only the node's position in the tree can change
- If an admin decides a sub-component needs its own tracking, they register it as
  a new equipment number and create a new leaf node for it

